title: Grateful Dead Live at Oakland Auditorium Arena on 1981-12-31
lineage: Master Cassettes (Dolby B)(Nakamichi CR-7A) > Tascam DA-3000 (DSF 1-bit/5.6 MHz)> dBpoweramp 2496 > Adobe Audition 3.01 > TLH flac2496
description:
Set I
Acoustic: Me And Bobby McGee*, Bye Bye Love*, Lucifer's Eyes*, Children Of The Eighties*, Banks Of The Ohio*
Set II
Electric-1: Shakedown Street, Me & My Uncle-> Mexicali Blues, Cold Rain & Snow, CC Rider**, It Must Have Been The Roses*-> Beat It On Down The Line, Big Boss Man**-> Minglewood Blues**, Don't Ease Me In
Set III
Electric-2: Iko Iko*, Playin' In The Band-> Terrapin Station-> Playin' In The Band-> Drums-> The Other One***-> Not Fade Away***-> Goin' Down The Road Feelin' Bad***-> Morning Dew; Encore aka Electric-3: Dark Star-> Bertha-> Good Lovin', It's All Over Now Baby Blue*
Comment
*W Joan Baez, **W Matt Kelly, ***W John Cippolina. First Set Acoustic; Bill Graham flew in on a joint at midnight

reviews.review_text:
Uniqueness I have hopped from one recorded version to another of this show since first obtaining a copy from Shaggy in the fall of 1987. It immediately became a classic in my internal pantheon, lighting up darker corners of my consciousness in various candle-lit caverns. Set II is the real pay dirt for me as the Playin' features one of the most unique jams I have ever heard from the Grateful Dead.

OK, Seattle '74 is 45 minutes. Fine. But in that (epic) jam, you'll find the Tiger and many familiar riffs and structures and runs from the amazing 72-74 run of Playin' jams. Other Playin' jams post-75 go to some exquisite places (looking at Playin-> Wheel-> Playin), but this one goes off ranch. Jerry picks up on a riff that repeats and loops, setting them off on a new path that has a unique script in my head.

Set three is glorious, but it's that Playin-> Terrapin-> Playin that is the real money for me here.

Inimitable.
